{"type":"message","id":"18104b84","parentId":"951d821f","timestamp":"2026-03-12T23:22:30.995Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me also add GitHub repo parsing. Looking at the shell script, it fetches GitHub data but the Python sender doesn't actually parse it. The GitHub data is in a variable but isn't logged in a parseable way. Let me check - the script logs \"GitHub data fetched successfully\" but doesn't log the actual data to the file.\n\nI should either:\n1. Update the shell script to log the GitHub data\n2. Or update the Python sender to fetch GitHub data directly\n\nLet me update the shell script to also log the GitHub data, and update the Python sender to parse it. Actually, let me just update the Python sender to fetch GitHub data itself since the shell script doesn't log it. But wait, the MEMORY.md says the daily ping should include top 10 trending repos.\n\n\nActually, I'm realizing the simplest fix is to have the Python script handle all the data fetching and formatting itself rather than trying to parse logs. The original recommendation was to stick with the existing shell script infrastructure, so I'll go with having the Python sender fetch GitHub data directly since the shell script already logs what we need for the other data.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"Now let me also update the GitHub section — the shell script fetches it but doesn't log it in a parseable way. I'll have the Python sender fetch GitHub data directly, and also add the proper format from MEMORY.md (top 10 trending repos, delta indicators):"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"89381916-9542-4dbd-b9b1-d0096b911a52","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/home/project/openclaw/daily-ping-sender.py","old_string":"import json\nimport re\nfrom datetime import datetime\nimport subprocess\nimport sys","new_string":"import json\nimport re\nfrom datetime import datetime, timedelta\nimport subprocess\nimport sys\nimport urllib.reques