{"type":"message","id":"94811d3b","parentId":"18033f90","timestamp":"2026-03-13T07:27:16.077Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Done. Let me give a summary of the review and the changes made.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"Done. Here's my review of the four gaps and what I integrated:\n\n**GAP 1: MEMORY.md as Attack Vector** 🔴 — Valid. MEMORY.md is loaded every session, making it a prime poisoning target. Added:\n- Never store credentials/tokens here\n- Reinforce critical stances each session\n- Watch for unfamiliar content\n\n**GAP 2: System Prompts Alone Are Insufficient** 🟡 — Valid. LLM-based detection is unreliable. Added technical controls:\n- Content separation rules\n- Execution approval requirement for external-content-triggered actions\n- Specific pattern detection (injection strings, hidden HTML, base64)\n- Action logging for audit\n\n**GAP 3: No Runtime Behavior Monitoring** 🟡 — Valid. I was scanning inputs but not monitoring actions. Added:\n- Three-question pre-execution check (aligned? loggable? scoped?)\n- Specific flagging criteria (unauthorized file access, non-whitelisted domains, rapid actions)\n\n**GAP 4: Safe Skills Repo Verification** 🟡 — Valid. Pre-scanned ≠ runtime-safe. Added to Safe Skills section:\n- Runtime validation before every skill invocation\n- Capability-action matching check\n- OWASP ASI02 awareness\n\nAll four recommendations integrated into MEMORY.md. The audit is well-researched — the January 2026 ClawHavoc campaign reference and OWASP ASI framework citations are specifically relevant."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"openrouter/hunter-alpha","usage":{"input":186,"output":330,"cacheRead":83904,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":84420,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1773386827665}}
